'''CSIR-Central Food Technological Research Institute''', abbreviated to '''CSIR-CFTRI''', is one of the 42 national research laboratories in [[India]], set up under the aegis of the [[Council of Scientific and Industrial Research]] (CSIR).<ref>{{cite web|title=CSIR Lab Directory|url=http://www.csir.res.in/external/heads/aboutcsir/lab_directory.htm|accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref> It was opened on 21 October 1950 in [[Mysore]], [[Karnataka]]. C.F.T.R.I. also has extended resource centers in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Lucknow]] and [[Mumbai]], rendering technical assistance to numerous entrepreneurs.

CSIR-CFTRI is a large and diversified laboratory headed by Dr. Jitendra Jadhav, Director, CSIR-CFTRI. Presently the institute has nearly 200 scientists, technologists, and engineers, and over 200 technicians, skilled workers, and support staff. There are sixteen [[research and development]] departments, including laboratories focusing on [[food biotechnology]], [[food microbiology|microbiology]], sensory science, and [[food safety]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CFTRI - R & D Departments|url=http://www.cftri.com/rddept.html|accessdate=19 January 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109135437/http://www.cftri.com/rddept.html|archivedate=9 November 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

The institute has designed over 300 products, processes, and equipment types. It holds several [[patent]]s and has released many publications. India is the world's second largest foodgrain, fruit and vegetable producer,<ref>{{cite web|title=Indian Agriculture|url=http://www.knowindia.net/agro.html|accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref> and the institute is engaged in research in the production and handling of [[cereal|grains]], [[Pulse (legume)|pulses]], [[Vegetable fats and oils|oilseeds]], [[spice]]s, [[fruit]]s, [[vegetable]]s, [[meat]], [[fish]], and [[poultry]].

The institute develops technologies to increase efficiency and reduce [[Post-harvest losses (vegetables)|postharvest losses]], add [[convenience]], increase [[export]], find new sources of food products, integrate [[human resources]] in food industries, reduce costs, and [[modernization|modernize]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2002-01-31/bangalore/27123713_1_food-processing-food-safety-food-industry | work=The Times Of India | title=CFTRI does its bit for tenth plan draft - The Times of India | date=31 January 2002}}</ref>

CSIR-CFTRI has developed over 270 products, processes and equipment designs, and close to 1600 licensees have availed themselves of 160 of these technologies for commercial exploitation.{{cn|date=March 2017}}

